v}}\n* [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324235304578438393688092634 Tsarnaev Family] (''[[Wall Street Journal]]'')\n\n{{Boston Athletic Association}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tsarnaev, Dzhokhar}}\n[[Category:American Islamists]]\n[[Category:Avar people]]\n[[Category:Chechen people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Boston Marathon bombing]]\n[[Category:Chechen Islamists]]\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:American spree killers]]\n[[Category:American murderers of children]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:American people imprisoned on charges of terrorism]]\n[[Category:American people of Avar descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Chechen descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Dagestani descent]]\n[[Category:American prisoners sentenced to death]]\n[[Category:American shooting survivors]]\n[[Category:American wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Kyrgyzstani emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by the United States federal government]]\n[[Category:People convicted on terrorism charges]]\n[[Category:People from Chuy Region]]\n[[Category:People imprisoned on charges of terrorism]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to death by the United States federal government]]\n[[Category:Inmates of ADX Florence]]\n[[Category:Islamist bombers]]\n[[Category:Russian expatriates in Kyrgyzstan]]\n[[Category:University of Massachusetts Dartmouth alumni]]\n[[Category:Cambridge Rindge and Latin School alumni]]\n[[Category:People with acquired American citizenship]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1000:b062:6faa:b0e5:5f77:5f98:198d", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eMIT killing, carjacking, firefight, and manhunt)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dzhokhar_Tsarnaev"}
{"title_page": "Charlamagne tha God", "text_new": "{{short description|American radio personality}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox presenter\n| name        = Charlamagne tha God\n| image       = Charlamagne Tha God 2014.png\n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = Charlamagne tha God in August 2014\n| birth_name  = Lenard Larry McKelvey\n| birth_place = [[Charleston, South Carolina]], U.S.\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1978|6|29}}\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| show        = ''The Breakfast Club'' <small>(co-host)</small>\n| station     = [[WWPR-FM|Power 105.1]]\n| timeslot    = 6:00 a.m.&nbsp;\u2013 10:00 a.m.\n| country     = United States\n| prevshow    = \n| web         =\n}}\n\n'''Lenard Larry McKelvey''' (born June 29, 1978), known professionally as '''Charlamagne tha God''', is an American [[radio presenter]], [[television personality]], and author.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/12/fashion/radio-host-Charlamagne-Tha-God-Celebrities.html?_r=0|title=Charlamagne Tha God: Keeping a Hot Seat Warm|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=August 2, 2016|date=December 11, 2013|first=Jacob|last=Bernstein}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/news/meet-hip-hops-howard-stern-charlamagne-tha-god-20140205 |title=Meet Hip-Hop's Howard Stern: Charlamagne tha God|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=February 5, 2014 |access-date=August 2, 2016|first=Simon|last=Vozick-Levinson}}</ref> He is a co-host of the nationally [[Broadcast syndication|syndicated]] radio show ''[[The Breakfast Club (radio show)|The Breakfast Club]]'' with [[DJ Envy]] and [[Angela Yee]], and stars in ''[[MTV2's Guy Code|Guy Code]]'', ''[[Guy Court]]'' and ''[[Girl Code]]''. He was also a [[VJ (media personality)|VJ]] for ''[[The Week in Jams]]'' with DJ Envy and Sofi Green. In 2015, Charlamagne began hosting the [[MTV2]] show ''[[Uncommon Sense with Charlamagne|Uncommon Sense]]''. He was previously on ''[[The Wendy Williams Experience]]'' with [[Wendy Williams]] on [[VH1]]. In the shock-jock tradition, one of Charlamagne's personal mantras is \"bite my tongue for no one.\"<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/celebrity/charlamagne-tha-god-black-privilege-book/|title=Charlamagne Tha God Calls New Book, Black Privilege, a 'Self-Help Guide for the Hood'|website=PEOPLE.com}}</ref>\nAlso, Charlamange, or Leonard larry, is an unprofessional ridiculously commented commentator payed by only more unintelligent people to talk about \"bullshit\" on \"his\" podcast the breakfast club. Which is totally useless do to the opinions he brings to interviews versus actual reasonable questions. And he's a fucking square whose just trying to be a gangster. Fuck you leonard larry, you puss.\n\n==Early life==\n\nMcKelvey was born to Larry Thomas McKelvey, a Jehovah's Witness-turned-Muslim<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://relevantmagazine.com/culture/charlamagne-tha-god/|title=CHARLAMAGNE THA GOD|date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> and his wife, an [[English language|English]] teacher and [[Jehovah's Witness]],<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/meet-hip-hops-howard-stern-charlamagne-tha-god-121133/|title=Meet Hip-Hop's Howard Stern: Charlamagne tha God|first1=Simon|last1=Vozick-Levinson|url-status=live|date=February 5, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/c087995b3d7244a78c4f230c7961b761|title=Charlamagne tha God has book coming next spring|date=November 1, 2016|website=AP NEWS}}</ref> on June 29, 1978,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvovermind.com/five-things-didnt-know-charlamagne-tha-god/|title=Five Things You Didn't Know About Charlamagne tha God|date=March 10, 2018|website=TVOvermind}}</ref> and grew up in [[Moncks Corner, South Carolina]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lehrman|first1=Jessica|url=http://www.vulture.com/2016/05/charlamagne-breakfast-club-hip-hop-morning-radio.html|title=Tha God of Radio|accessdate=May 15, 2016|publisher=Vulture|date=May 3, 2016}}</ref> As a teenager, McKelvey began selling drugs, and was arrested twice for possession of [[marijuana]] and [[cocaine]] with intent to distribute. After witnessing a shooting from the back seat of a car, McKelvey was arrested for a third time. His father refused to pay his bail money, and McKelvey remained in jail for 41 days. Eventually, he called his mother, who paid for his bail and McKelvey was released.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Career==\n\n=== Radio ===\nAfter being released from the county jail, McKelvey began attending night school and eventually got a job as a radio intern.<ref name=\":0\" /> He went on to become second [[microphone|mic]] to radio host [[Wendy Williams]]. He developed the stage name of Charlamagne, taken from his [[pseudonym]] as a drug dealer, \"Charles,\" and created a new persona based on King [[Charlemagne]], who ruled much of Western Europe as part of the Carolingian Empire<ref name=\"auto\"/> in the late 700s and early 800s, whom he read about at night school. He added \"Tha God\" because it \"sounded cool.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> At this point, his unorthodox and upfront questioning of hip-hop/R&B artists on radio raised his public profile but also caused rifts between himself and the guests of the show. He was laid off from the program in 2008.<ref name=\":0\" /> Relations between Charlamagne and Williams deteriorated, though Charlamagne has stated numerous times on his show ''[[The Breakfast Club (radio show)|The Breakfast Club]]'' that he views Williams as a mentor and bears no ill feeling toward her.\n\nIn 2010, Charlamagne began hosting ''[[The Breakfast Club (radio show)|The Breakfast Club]]'', alongside [[DJ Envy]] and [[Angela Yee]] on [[WWPR-FM]] in [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], along with its national television [[simulcast]] on [[Revolt (TV network)|Revolt]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Once part of the show, Charlamagne gave himself the title \"Prime Minister of Pissing People Off, the Architect of Aggravation, and the Ruler of Rubbing People the Wrong Way.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Black privilege : opportunity comes to those who create it|last=Charlamagne Tha God, 1980-|publisher=|isbn=9781501145308|edition=First Touchstone hardcover|location=New York|pages=219|oclc=958459919|date = April 18, 2017}}</ref> In 2014, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' nicknamed him \"hip-hop's [[Howard Stern]].\"<ref name=\"vozicklevinson2014\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/meet-hip-hops-howard-stern-charlamagne-tha-god-121133/|title=Meet Hip-Hop's Howard Stern: Charlamagne tha God|last=Vozick-Levinson|first=Simon|date=5 February 2014|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709215605/https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/meet-hip-hops-howard-stern-charlamagne-tha-god-121133/|archive-date=8 July 2018|quote=Charlamagne is sitting in the greenroom at [[MTV2]], where he just taped an episode of his new late-night TV talk show, Charlamagne and Friends. It\u2019s the logical next step for the outspoken commentator, a self-styled <b>hip-hop Howard Stern</b> who prides himself on speaking his mind, no matter the fallout (like the time he said of [[Justin Bieber]], \u201cDon\u2019t be a waste of good white skin\u201d).}}</ref>\n\n=== Television ===\n[[File:Charlamagne Tha God at MTV Movie Awards 2012.jpg|thumb|Charlamagne interviewed about ''Guy Code'' at the [[MTV Movie Awards]] 2012]]\nBeginning on November 15, 2011, Charlamagne served as a cast member of ''[[MTV2's Guy Code|Guy Code]]'', a comedy television show on [[MTV2]] that talks about a special code of conduct just for men. The show ended in March 2015. He formerly starred on the MTV2 show ''Charlamagne & Friends''<ref name=\"auto\"/> At the end of 2013 and 2014, he co-hosted [[MTV New Year's]] live from [[Times Square]] and in 2015 he was a correspondent for the [[2015 MTV Video Music Awards]] pre-show.<ref>{{cite news|title=MTV Is Ringing in 2014 with the \"Girl Code Presents: New Year's Code\" Special Starting December 31 at 10:00 P.M. ET/PT|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2013/12/11/mtv-is-ringing-in-2014-with-the-girl-code-presents-new-years-code-special-starting-december-31-at-1000-pm-et-pt-401115/20131211mtv01/|accessdate=February 26, 2018|publisher=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=December 11, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ring in 2015 with 'MTV's New Year's Eve 2015' Hosted by Victoria Justice & Charlamagne|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/network-press-releases/ring-in-2015-with-mtvs-new-years-eve-2015-hosted-by-victoria-justice-charlamagne/|accessdate=February 26, 2018|publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]]|date=December 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.mtvasia.com/show/mtv-vma-2015/2015-pre-show/2015-vma-pre-show-charlamagne-carly-amp-the-puparazzi-pen-1235950?autoplay=1 |title=Music: Listen to Free Music, Watch New Music Videos &#124; MTV Asia |publisher=Music.mtvasia.com |date= |accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> He currently stars and hosts MTV2 show ''Uncommon Sense with Charlamagne tha God''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Breakfast Club Host Charlamagne tha God and Tyga Land Their Own Shows on MTV2 |date=April 17, 2015 |publisher=Music Times |url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/35966/20150417/breakfast-club-host-charlamagne-tha-god-tyga-land-shows-mtv2.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150802165728/http://www.musictimes.com/articles/35966/20150417/breakfast-club-host-charlamagne-tha-god-tyga-land-shows-mtv2.htm|archivedate=August 2, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Charlamagne puts his 'Uncommon Sense' to good use on TV and social media |date=July 5, 2015|publisher=Cynopsis Media |url=http://cynopsis.com/cyncity/charlamagne-uncommon-sense/ }}</ref> He currently narrates the BET Show, ''Inside the Label''.\n\n=== YouTube ===\nCharlamagne currently hosts a YouTube series called ''Emerging Hollywood'' which is posted on [[The Hollywood Reporter]]'s YouTube channel. On this show, Charlamagne speaks with Hollywood professionals to discuss various political topics. His past guests on the show include [[Trevor Noah]] and [[Jameela Jamil]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.51278/title.charlamagne-tha-god-trevor-noah-explore-racial-diversity-in-hollywood-beyond|title=Charlamagne Tha God & Trevor Noah Explore Racial Diversity In Hollywood & Beyond|last=http://hiphopdx.com|first=HipHopDX-|date=2019-05-03|website=HipHopDX|access-date=2019-05-10}}</ref> With fellow MTV2 personality [[Andrew Schulz]], he hosts ''[[The Brilliant Idiots (podcast)|The Brilliant Idiots]]'' podcast on [[Combat Jack]]'s [[Loud Speakers Network]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ng|first1=Philiana|title=MTV2 Renews 'Charlamagne & Friends' for Season 2 (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/mtv2-renews-charlamagne-friends-season-661401|accessdate=February 26, 2018|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=December 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Robertson|first1=Iyana|title=Let Charlamagne tha God and Andrew Schulz Sort Through Your Issues of Race in Hip-Hop|url=https://www.vibe.com/2015/02/brilliant-idiots-race-charlamagne-andrew-schulz/|accessdate=February 26, 2018|work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|date=February 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Writing ===\nIn 2017, his book ''Black Privilege: Opportunity Comes to Those Who Create It'', which he called \"a self-help guide for the hood,\"<ref name=\"auto1\"/> was published by the [[Simon & Schuster]] imprint Touchstone. Steven Kurutz of ''[[The New York Times]]'' gave the book a mostly positive review, describing ''Black Privilege'' as \"a street-smart self-help guide\" with typically blunt advice offered in eight different principles.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/17/style/charlamagne-tha-god-book.html |title=Charlamagne Tha God Puts His Straight Talk in a Book |last=Kurutz |first=Steven |website=The New York Times |date=April 17, 2017}}</ref> The book was ranked sixth in the May 7, 2017, [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''New York Times'' list of best-selling]] hardback non-fiction.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/hardcover-nonfiction/ |title=Hardcover Nonfiction Books - Best Sellers |newspaper=The New York Times |date=May 7, 2017|author= |accessdate= April 29, 2017}}</ref> McKelvey's second book, ''Shook One: Anxiety Playing Tricks on Me'' was released on October 23, 2018.<ref>{{cite book|title=Shook One: Anxiety Playing Tricks on Me|author=Charlamagne tha God|publisher=Atria Books|date=2018|isbn=978-1501193255}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\n\nCharlamagne is considered a controversial figure in the world of radio due to his willingness to ask personal questions and his open criticism of musicians, athletes and other media personalities. Charlamagne's direct criticism of guests during interviews has resulted in numerous altercations and arguments on air.\n\n===Lil' Mama===\nIn a 2011 interview with Lil' Mama, Charlamagne confronted the rapper, saying, \"you come off as cocky\" and insinuated that she hadn't accomplished enough to be cocky. He additionally alluded to his belief that her criticism of other rappers' behavior should be communicated through her music rather than stated in the media. He provoked the rapper/actress by calling her the \"voice of the young struggle-face,\" digging at her appearance.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2495794/lil-mama-defends-nicki-minaj-comments-breaks-down-on-air/|title=Lil Mama Defends Nicki Minaj Comments, Breaks Down Crying On Air|first=MTV News|last=Staff|website=MTV News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ebony.com/entertainment/the-breakfast-club-and-all-its-problematic-banter/|title='The Breakfast Club' And All Its Problematic Banter: Is It Time For A Boycott?|first=Zahara|last=Hill|date=August 3, 2017|website=EBONY}}</ref> He went on to say, \"you're young and you have an old face; like [[Drake (rapper)|Drake]] says, 'I'm really too young to be looking this old.'\"<ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2015/09/lil-mama-interview|title=Inside the Dramatic Exit and Surprising Return of Lil Mama|website=Complex}}</ref> \n\nShe returned to ''The Breakfast Club'' for a less tense interview on January 12, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3C0iE8v4i7k|title=Lil Mama Interview at The Breakfast Club Power 105.1 (01/12/2016)|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\n=== Birdman ===\n\nRapper [[Birdman (rapper)|Birdman]] walked out of his interview with ''The Breakfast Club'' on April 22, 2016, after just over two minutes, claiming the hosts, specifically Charlamagne, were not \"putting respect on his name\". Birdman was angry at the hosts allowing artists such as [[Trick Daddy]] and [[Rick Ross]] to appear on the show and make disparaging remarks about him. Charlamagne questioned why Birdman was angry at him and not the artists themselves, and Birdman left the interview after just over two minutes. The interview went viral and resulted in numerous memes based on the incident. It is the shortest interview in ''Breakfast Club'' history.<ref name=\"platon2016\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/7341706/birdman-breakfast-club-short-interview|title=Birdman Asks the Breakfast Club to 'Respect My Name' in Swift Sit-Down: Watch|last=Platon|first=Adelle|date=2016-04-22|website=Billboard|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425055236/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/7341706/birdman-breakfast-club-short-interview|archive-date=25 April 2016|access-date=4 March 2020|quote=A Breakfast Club interview went left on Friday morning (April 22[, 2016]) after Cash Money chief [[Birdman (rapper)|Birdman]] paid Charlamagne Tha God, Angela Yee and DJ Envy a two-and-a-half-minute visit.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4jLT7GQYNhI|title=Birdman Goes Off On The Breakfast Club Power 105.1 (04/22/2016)|date=April 22, 2016|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n=== Fredro Starr ===\n\nIn the summer of 2014, hip-hop group [[Onyx (hip hop group)|Onyx]] appeared on ''The Breakfast Club''. Tensions rose between member [[Fredro Starr]] and Charlamagne after Charlamagne brought up Starr allegedly receiving oral sex from singer [[Brandy Norwood]]. Starr responded by branding Charlamagne a \"pussy\", and made reference to Charlamagne being attacked on camera outside of the [[Power 105.1]] building. Starr was eventually calmed down by fellow Onyx member [[Sticky Fingaz]], and eventually finished the interview, however, the resulting video went viral, and led to Starr becoming the face of ''The Breakfast Club''<nowiki/>'s \"P.O. Meter\", a running joke used to measure a guest's perceived anger.<ref>{{Cite web|archive-url=http://archive.massappeal.com/charlamagne-tha-god-tries-to-catch-the-fade-from-onyxs-fredro-starr/|archive-date=2 April 2019|url=https://massappeal.com|title=Charlamagne Tha God Tries to Catch the Fade From Onyx's Fredro Starr|website=Mass Appeal}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.factmag.com/2014/08/03/charlamagne-tha-god-breakfast-club-onyx-fredro-starr/|title=Fredro Starr loses his shit at Charlamagne Tha God in intense Breakfast Club interview|date=August 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Beanie Sigel ===\n\nOn October 11, 2016, rapper [[Beanie Sigel]] appeared on ''The Breakfast Club'' to conduct an interview. Sigel grew annoyed with Charlamagne's perceived attempts at escalating the feud between himself and [[Meek Mill]], complaining that Charlamagne was \"harping on the issue\". Charlamagne branded Sigel a hypocrite, who responded by saying he felt Charlamagne was a \"sucker\" for letting Fredro Starr disrespect him live on air, and criticised him for making rapper [[Lil Mama]] cry, calling him a coward. Siegel threatened to walk out numerous times before eventually finishing the interview. The subsequent video went viral.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rap-up.com/2016/10/11/beanie-sigel-confronts-charlamagne-tha-god-over-meek-mill/|title=Beanie Sigel Confronts Charlamagne Tha God Over Meek Mill|website=Rap-Up}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rIVzS2PWS_4|title=Beanie Sigel On What Went Down With Meek Mill and The Game|date=October 11, 2016|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n=== Lil Duval ===\nIn July 2017, comedian [[Lil Duval]] joked on ''The Breakfast Club'' show about killing a sex partner if she turned out to be a [[transgender woman]]. Charlamagne tha God, while noting that killing a trans person was a [[hate crime]], stated that women not disclosing their trans status were \"taking away a person's power of choice\" and \"should go to jail or something\". In response, trans activists, including [[Raquel Willis]] and [[Elle Hearns]], called for the show to be boycotted or cancelled.<ref name=\"essence-31jul2017\">{{cite magazine|title=Lil Duval Jokes About Murdering Transgender Women, Leads To 'The Breakfast Club' Boycott|url=http://www.essence.com/entertainment/lil-duval-the-breakfast-club-boycott-transphobia|accessdate=October 3, 2017|magazine=[[Essence (magazine)|Essence]]|date=July 31, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes-6aug2017\">{{cite news|last1=Eligon|first1=John|title=Transgender African-Americans' Open Wound: 'We're Considered a Joke'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/06/us/black-transgender-lil-duval.html|accessdate=October 3, 2017|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 6, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"root-1aug2017\">{{cite magazine|last1=Starr|first1=Terrell Jermaine|title=Trans Black Women Are Petitioning Charlamagne tha God Over Transphobic Comments on Show|url=http://www.theroot.com/trans-black-women-are-petitioning-charlamagne-over-tra-1797419756|accessdate=October 3, 2017|magazine=[[The Root (magazine)|The Root]]|date=August 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Elizabeth Warren ===\nIn June 2019, Charlamagne interviewed Democratic Presidential candidate [[Elizabeth Warren]], whereupon he confronted her about her claims of [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] ancestry. In the interview he compared her to [[Rachel Dolezal]].<ref>{{Citation|publisher=CNN|title=Charlamagne Tha God compares Elizabeth Warren to Rachel Dolezal|date=2019-06-13|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rv1MaSApR8M|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*''South Crack: The Album'' (2008)\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''Kiss & Tail: The Hollywood Jumpoff''\n| Himself\n| \n|-\n| 2011\u20132015\n| ''[[Guy Code]]''\n| Himself\n| Stars in along with [[Lil Duval]]\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''This Thing of Ours''\n| \"Shottah\"\n| \n|-\n| 2012\n| ''Hip-Hop POV''\n| Himself\n| \n|-\n| 2012\n| ''Hood State of Union''\n| Himself\n| \n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[The Week in Jams]]''\n| Himself\n| Host in along with [[DJ Envy]] & Sofi Green\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Girl Code]]''\n| Himself\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Guy Code Honors]]''\n| Himself\n| A one and a half-hour show that honored the superheroes and villains from the 2013 [[San Diego Comic-Con International|Comic-Con]] in [[San Diego]], [[California]]\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''Charlamagne & Friends''\n| Himself\n| 2013\u2013Present\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Guy Court]]''\n| Himself\n|\n|-\n| 2013, 2015\n| ''[[Wild 'N Out]]''\n| Himself\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Ride Along (film)|Ride Along]]''\n| Cop\n| Cameo appearance\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Catfish: The TV Show]]''\n| Himself\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 2015\u2013present\n| ''[[Uncommon Sense with Charlamagne]]''\n| Himself \n| Host\n|-\n| 2015 \n| ''[[Empire (2015 TV series)|Empire]]''\n| Himself \n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Grow House (film)|Grow House]]''\n| Black Jesus\n| Acting debut\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Bodied]]''\n|Hunnid Gramz\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Twitter|cthagod}}\n\n{{Gullah topics|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Charlamagne tha God}}\n[[Category:Radio personalities from New York City]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:African-American male comedians]]\n[[Category:American male comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:African-American comedians]]\n[[Category:African-American radio personalities]]\n[[Category:People from Moncks Corner, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Gullah]]\n[[Category:Catfish the TV Show hosts]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American radio personality}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox presenter\n| name        = Charlamagne tha God\n| image       = Charlamagne Tha God 2014.png\n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = Charlamagne tha God in August 2014\n| birth_name  = Lenard Larry McKelvey\n| birth_place = [[Charleston, South Carolina]], U.S.\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1978|6|29}}\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| show        = ''The Breakfast Club'' <small>(co-host)</small>\n| station     = [[WWPR-FM|Power 105.1]]\n| timeslot    = 6:00 a.m.&nbsp;\u2013 10:00 a.m.\n| country     = United States\n| prevshow    = \n| web         =\n}}\n\n'''Lenard Larry McKelvey''' (born June 29, 1978), known professionally as '''Charlamagne tha God''', is an American [[radio presenter]], [[television personality]], and author.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/12/fashion/radio-host-Charlamagne-Tha-God-Celebrities.html?_r=0|title=Charlamagne Tha God: Keeping a Hot Seat Warm|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=August 2, 2016|date=December 11, 2013|first=Jacob|last=Bernstein}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/news/meet-hip-hops-howard-stern-charlamagne-tha-god-20140205 |title=Meet Hip-Hop's Howard Stern: Charlamagne tha God|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=February 5, 2014 |access-date=August 2, 2016|first=Simon|last=Vozick-Levinson}}</ref> He is a co-host of the nationally [[Broadcast syndication|syndicated]] radio show ''[[The Breakfast Club (radio show)|The Breakfast Club]]'' with [[DJ Envy]] and [[Angela Yee]], and stars in ''[[MTV2's Guy Code|Guy Code]]'', ''[[Guy Court]]'' and ''[[Girl Code]]''. He was also a [[VJ (media personality)|VJ]] for ''[[The Week in Jams]]'' with DJ Envy and Sofi Green. In 2015, Charlamagne began hosting the [[MTV2]] show ''[[Uncommon Sense with Charlamagne|Uncommon Sense]]''. He was previously on ''[[The Wendy Williams Experience]]'' with [[Wendy Williams]] on [[VH1]]. In the shock-jock tradition, one of Charlamagne's personal mantras is \"bite my tongue for no one.\"<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/celebrity/charlamagne-tha-god-black-privilege-book/|title=Charlamagne Tha God Calls New Book, Black Privilege, a 'Self-Help Guide for the Hood'|website=PEOPLE.com}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nMcKelvey was born to Larry Thomas McKelvey, a Jehovah's Witness-turned-Muslim<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://relevantmagazine.com/culture/charlamagne-tha-god/|title=CHARLAMAGNE THA GOD|date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> and his wife, an [[English language|English]] teacher and [[Jehovah's Witness]],<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/meet-hip-hops-howard-stern-charlamagne-tha-god-121133/|title=Meet Hip-Hop's Howard Stern: Charlamagne tha God|first1=Simon|last1=Vozick-Levinson|url-status=live|date=February 5, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/c087995b3d7244a78c4f230c7961b761|title=Charlamagne tha God has book coming next spring|date=November 1, 2016|website=AP NEWS}}</ref> on June 29, 1978,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvovermind.com/five-things-didnt-know-charlamagne-tha-god/|title=Five Things You Didn't Know About Charlamagne tha God|date=March 10, 2018|website=TVOvermind}}</ref> and grew up in [[Moncks Corner, South Carolina]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lehrman|first1=Jessica|url=http://www.vulture.com/2016/05/charlamagne-breakfast-club-hip-hop-morning-radio.html|title=Tha God of Radio|accessdate=May 15, 2016|publisher=Vulture|date=May 3, 2016}}</ref> As a teenager, McKelvey began selling drugs, and was arrested twice for possession of [[marijuana]] and [[cocaine]] with intent to distribute. After witnessing a shooting from the back seat of a car, McKelvey was arrested for a third time. His father refused to pay his bail money, and McKelvey remained in jail for 41 days. Eventually, he called his mother, who paid for his bail and McKelvey was released.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Career==\n\n=== Radio ===\nAfter being released from the county jail, McKelvey began attending night school and eventually got a job as a radio intern.<ref name=\":0\" /> He went on to become second [[microphone|mic]] to radio host [[Wendy Williams]]. He developed the stage name of Charlamagne, taken from his [[pseudonym]] as a drug dealer, \"Charles,\" and created a new persona based on King [[Charlemagne]], who ruled much of Western Europe as part of the Carolingian Empire<ref name=\"auto\"/> in the late 700s and early 800s, whom he read about at night school. He added \"Tha God\" because it \"sounded cool.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> At this point, his unorthodox and upfront questioning of hip-hop/R&B artists on radio raised his public profile but also caused rifts between himself and the guests of the show. He was laid off from the program in 2008.<ref name=\":0\" /> Relations between Charlamagne and Williams deteriorated, though Charlamagne has stated numerous times on his show ''[[The Breakfast Club (radio show)|The Breakfast Club]]'' that he views Williams as a mentor and bears no ill feeling toward her.\n\nIn 2010, Charlamagne began hosting ''[[The Breakfast Club (radio show)|The Breakfast Club]]'', alongside [[DJ Envy]] and [[Angela Yee]] on [[WWPR-FM]] in [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], along with its national television [[simulcast]] on [[Revolt (TV network)|Revolt]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Once part of the show, Charlamagne gave himself the title \"Prime Minister of Pissing People Off, the Architect of Aggravation, and the Ruler of Rubbing People the Wrong Way.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Black privilege : opportunity comes to those who create it|last=Charlamagne Tha God, 1980-|publisher=|isbn=9781501145308|edition=First Touchstone hardcover|location=New York|pages=219|oclc=958459919|date = April 18, 2017}}</ref> In 2014, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' nicknamed him \"hip-hop's [[Howard Stern]].\"<ref name=\"vozicklevinson2014\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/meet-hip-hops-howard-stern-charlamagne-tha-god-121133/|title=Meet Hip-Hop's Howard Stern: Charlamagne tha God|last=Vozick-Levinson|first=Simon|date=5 February 2014|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709215605/https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/meet-hip-hops-howard-stern-charlamagne-tha-god-121133/|archive-date=8 July 2018|quote=Charlamagne is sitting in the greenroom at [[MTV2]], where he just taped an episode of his new late-night TV talk show, Charlamagne and Friends. It\u2019s the logical next step for the outspoken commentator, a self-styled <b>hip-hop Howard Stern</b> who prides himself on speaking his mind, no matter the fallout (like the time he said of [[Justin Bieber]], \u201cDon\u2019t be a waste of good white skin\u201d).}}</ref>\n\n=== Television ===\n[[File:Charlamagne Tha God at MTV Movie Awards 2012.jpg|thumb|Charlamagne interviewed about ''Guy Code'' at the [[MTV Movie Awards]] 2012]]\nBeginning on November 15, 2011, Charlamagne served as a cast member of ''[[MTV2's Guy Code|Guy Code]]'', a comedy television show on [[MTV2]] that talks about a special code of conduct just for men. The show ended in March 2015. He formerly starred on the MTV2 show ''Charlamagne & Friends''<ref name=\"auto\"/> At the end of 2013 and 2014, he co-hosted [[MTV New Year's]] live from [[Times Square]] and in 2015 he was a correspondent for the [[2015 MTV Video Music Awards]] pre-show.<ref>{{cite news|title=MTV Is Ringing in 2014 with the \"Girl Code Presents: New Year's Code\" Special Starting December 31 at 10:00 P.M. ET/PT|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2013/12/11/mtv-is-ringing-in-2014-with-the-girl-code-presents-new-years-code-special-starting-december-31-at-1000-pm-et-pt-401115/20131211mtv01/|accessdate=February 26, 2018|publisher=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=December 11, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ring in 2015 with 'MTV's New Year's Eve 2015' Hosted by Victoria Justice & Charlamagne|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/network-press-releases/ring-in-2015-with-mtvs-new-years-eve-2015-hosted-by-victoria-justice-charlamagne/|accessdate=February 26, 2018|publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]]|date=December 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.mtvasia.com/show/mtv-vma-2015/2015-pre-show/2015-vma-pre-show-charlamagne-carly-amp-the-puparazzi-pen-1235950?autoplay=1 |title=Music: Listen to Free Music, Watch New Music Videos &#124; MTV Asia |publisher=Music.mtvasia.com |date= |accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> He currently stars and hosts MTV2 show ''Uncommon Sense with Charlamagne tha God''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Breakfast Club Host Charlamagne tha God and Tyga Land Their Own Shows on MTV2 |date=April 17, 2015 |publisher=Music Times |url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/35966/20150417/breakfast-club-host-charlamagne-tha-god-tyga-land-shows-mtv2.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150802165728/http://www.musictimes.com/articles/35966/20150417/breakfast-club-host-charlamagne-tha-god-tyga-land-shows-mtv2.htm|archivedate=August 2, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Charlamagne puts his 'Uncommon Sense' to good use on TV and social media |date=July 5, 2015|publisher=Cynopsis Media |url=http://cynopsis.com/cyncity/charlamagne-uncommon-sense/ }}</ref> He currently narrates the BET Show, ''Inside the Label''.\n\n=== YouTube ===\nCharlamagne currently hosts a YouTube series called ''Emerging Hollywood'' which is posted on [[The Hollywood Reporter]]'s YouTube channel. On this show, Charlamagne speaks with Hollywood professionals to discuss various political topics. His past guests on the show include [[Trevor Noah]] and [[Jameela Jamil]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.51278/title.charlamagne-tha-god-trevor-noah-explore-racial-diversity-in-hollywood-beyond|title=Charlamagne Tha God & Trevor Noah Explore Racial Diversity In Hollywood & Beyond|last=http://hiphopdx.com|first=HipHopDX-|date=2019-05-03|website=HipHopDX|access-date=2019-05-10}}</ref> With fellow MTV2 personality [[Andrew Schulz]], he hosts ''[[The Brilliant Idiots (podcast)|The Brilliant Idiots]]'' podcast on [[Combat Jack]]'s [[Loud Speakers Network]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ng|first1=Philiana|title=MTV2 Renews 'Charlamagne & Friends' for Season 2 (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/mtv2-renews-charlamagne-friends-season-661401|accessdate=February 26, 2018|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=December 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Robertson|first1=Iyana|title=Let Charlamagne tha God and Andrew Schulz Sort Through Your Issues of Race in Hip-Hop|url=https://www.vibe.com/2015/02/brilliant-idiots-race-charlamagne-andrew-schulz/|accessdate=February 26, 2018|work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|date=February 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Writing ===\nIn 2017, his book ''Black Privilege: Opportunity Comes to Those Who Create It'', which he called \"a self-help guide for the hood,\"<ref name=\"auto1\"/> was published by the [[Simon & Schuster]] imprint Touchstone. Steven Kurutz of ''[[The New York Times]]'' gave the book a mostly positive review, describing ''Black Privilege'' as \"a street-smart self-help guide\" with typically blunt advice offered in eight different principles.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/17/style/charlamagne-tha-god-book.html |title=Charlamagne Tha God Puts His Straight Talk in a Book |last=Kurutz |first=Steven |website=The New York Times |date=April 17, 2017}}</ref> The book was ranked sixth in the May 7, 2017, [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''New York Times'' list of best-selling]] hardback non-fiction.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/hardcover-nonfiction/ |title=Hardcover Nonfiction Books - Best Sellers |newspaper=The New York Times |date=May 7, 2017|author= |accessdate= April 29, 2017}}</ref> McKelvey's second book, ''Shook One: Anxiety Playing Tricks on Me'' was released on October 23, 2018.<ref>{{cite book|title=Shook One: Anxiety Playing Tricks on Me|author=Charlamagne tha God|publisher=Atria Books|date=2018|isbn=978-1501193255}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\n\nCharlamagne is considered a controversial figure in the world of radio due to his willingness to ask personal questions and his open criticism of musicians, athletes and other media personalities. Charlamagne's direct criticism of guests during interviews has resulted in numerous altercations and arguments on air.\n\n===Lil' Mama===\nIn a 2011 interview with Lil' Mama, Charlamagne confronted the rapper, saying, \"you come off as cocky\" and insinuated that she hadn't accomplished enough to be cocky. He additionally alluded to his belief that her criticism of other rappers' behavior should be communicated through her music rather than stated in the media. He provoked the rapper/actress by calling her the \"voice of the young struggle-face,\" digging at her appearance.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2495794/lil-mama-defends-nicki-minaj-comments-breaks-down-on-air/|title=Lil Mama Defends Nicki Minaj Comments, Breaks Down Crying On Air|first=MTV News|last=Staff|website=MTV News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ebony.com/entertainment/the-breakfast-club-and-all-its-problematic-banter/|title='The Breakfast Club' And All Its Problematic Banter: Is It Time For A Boycott?|first=Zahara|last=Hill|date=August 3, 2017|website=EBONY}}</ref> He went on to say, \"you're young and you have an old face; like [[Drake (rapper)|Drake]] says, 'I'm really too young to be looking this old.'\"<ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2015/09/lil-mama-interview|title=Inside the Dramatic Exit and Surprising Return of Lil Mama|website=Complex}}</ref> \n\nShe returned to ''The Breakfast Club'' for a less tense interview on January 12, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3C0iE8v4i7k|title=Lil Mama Interview at The Breakfast Club Power 105.1 (01/12/2016)|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\n=== Birdman ===\n\nRapper [[Birdman (rapper)|Birdman]] walked out of his interview with ''The Breakfast Club'' on April 22, 2016, after just over two minutes, claiming the hosts, specifically Charlamagne, were not \"putting respect on his name\". Birdman was angry at the hosts allowing artists such as [[Trick Daddy]] and [[Rick Ross]] to appear on the show and make disparaging remarks about him. Charlamagne questioned why Birdman was angry at him and not the artists themselves, and Birdman left the interview after just over two minutes. The interview went viral and resulted in numerous memes based on the incident. It is the shortest interview in ''Breakfast Club'' history.<ref name=\"platon2016\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/7341706/birdman-breakfast-club-short-interview|title=Birdman Asks the Breakfast Club to 'Respect My Name' in Swift Sit-Down: Watch|last=Platon|first=Adelle|date=2016-04-22|website=Billboard|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425055236/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/7341706/birdman-breakfast-club-short-interview|archive-date=25 April 2016|access-date=4 March 2020|quote=A Breakfast Club interview went left on Friday morning (April 22[, 2016]) after Cash Money chief [[Birdman (rapper)|Birdman]] paid Charlamagne Tha God, Angela Yee and DJ Envy a two-and-a-half-minute visit.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4jLT7GQYNhI|title=Birdman Goes Off On The Breakfast Club Power 105.1 (04/22/2016)|date=April 22, 2016|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n=== Fredro Starr ===\n\nIn the summer of 2014, hip-hop group [[Onyx (hip hop group)|Onyx]] appeared on ''The Breakfast Club''. Tensions rose between member [[Fredro Starr]] and Charlamagne after Charlamagne brought up Starr allegedly receiving oral sex from singer [[Brandy Norwood]]. Starr responded by branding Charlamagne a \"pussy\", and made reference to Charlamagne being attacked on camera outside of the [[Power 105.1]] building. Starr was eventually calmed down by fellow Onyx member [[Sticky Fingaz]], and eventually finished the interview, however, the resulting video went viral, and led to Starr becoming the face of ''The Breakfast Club''<nowiki/>'s \"P.O. Meter\", a running joke used to measure a guest's perceived anger.<ref>{{Cite web|archive-url=http://archive.massappeal.com/charlamagne-tha-god-tries-to-catch-the-fade-from-onyxs-fredro-starr/|archive-date=2 April 2019|url=https://massappeal.com|title=Charlamagne Tha God Tries to Catch the Fade From Onyx's Fredro Starr|website=Mass Appeal}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.factmag.com/2014/08/03/charlamagne-tha-god-breakfast-club-onyx-fredro-starr/|title=Fredro Starr loses his shit at Charlamagne Tha God in intense Breakfast Club interview|date=August 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Beanie Sigel ===\n\nOn October 11, 2016, rapper [[Beanie Sigel]] appeared on ''The Breakfast Club'' to conduct an interview. Sigel grew annoyed with Charlamagne's perceived attempts at escalating the feud between himself and [[Meek Mill]], complaining that Charlamagne was \"harping on the issue\". Charlamagne branded Sigel a hypocrite, who responded by saying he felt Charlamagne was a \"sucker\" for letting Fredro Starr disrespect him live on air, and criticised him for making rapper [[Lil Mama]] cry, calling him a coward. Siegel threatened to walk out numerous times before eventually finishing the interview. The subsequent video went viral.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rap-up.com/2016/10/11/beanie-sigel-confronts-charlamagne-tha-god-over-meek-mill/|title=Beanie Sigel Confronts Charlamagne Tha God Over Meek Mill|website=Rap-Up}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rIVzS2PWS_4|title=Beanie Sigel On What Went Down With Meek Mill and The Game|date=October 11, 2016|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n=== Lil Duval ===\nIn July 2017, comedian [[Lil Duval]] joked on ''The Breakfast Club'' show about killing a sex partner if she turned out to be a [[transgender woman]]. Charlamagne tha God, while noting that killing a trans person was a [[hate crime]], stated that women not disclosing their trans status were \"taking away a person's power of choice\" and \"should go to jail or something\". In response, trans activists, including [[Raquel Willis]] and [[Elle Hearns]], called for the show to be boycotted or cancelled.<ref name=\"essence-31jul2017\">{{cite magazine|title=Lil Duval Jokes About Murdering Transgender Women, Leads To 'The Breakfast Club' Boycott|url=http://www.essence.com/entertainment/lil-duval-the-breakfast-club-boycott-transphobia|accessdate=October 3, 2017|magazine=[[Essence (magazine)|Essence]]|date=July 31, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes-6aug2017\">{{cite news|last1=Eligon|first1=John|title=Transgender African-Americans' Open Wound: 'We're Considered a Joke'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/06/us/black-transgender-lil-duval.html|accessdate=October 3, 2017|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 6, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"root-1aug2017\">{{cite magazine|last1=Starr|first1=Terrell Jermaine|title=Trans Black Women Are Petitioning Charlamagne tha God Over Transphobic Comments on Show|url=http://www.theroot.com/trans-black-women-are-petitioning-charlamagne-over-tra-1797419756|accessdate=October 3, 2017|magazine=[[The Root (magazine)|The Root]]|date=August 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Elizabeth Warren ===\nIn June 2019, Charlamagne interviewed Democratic Presidential candidate [[Elizabeth Warren]], whereupon he confronted her about her claims of [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] ancestry. In the interview he compared her to [[Rachel Dolezal]].<ref>{{Citation|publisher=CNN|title=Charlamagne Tha God compares Elizabeth Warren to Rachel Dolezal|date=2019-06-13|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rv1MaSApR8M|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*''South Crack: The Album'' (2008)\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''Kiss & Tail: The Hollywood Jumpoff''\n| Himself\n| \n|-\n| 2011\u20132015\n| ''[[Guy Code]]''\n| Himself\n| Stars in along with [[Lil Duval]]\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''This Thing of Ours''\n| \"Shottah\"\n| \n|-\n| 2012\n| ''Hip-Hop POV''\n| Himself\n| \n|-\n| 2012\n| ''Hood State of Union''\n| Himself\n| \n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[The Week in Jams]]''\n| Himself\n| Host in along with [[DJ Envy]] & Sofi Green\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Girl Code]]''\n| Himself\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Guy Code Honors]]''\n| Himself\n| A one and a half-hour show that honored the superheroes and villains from the 2013 [[San Diego Comic-Con International|Comic-Con]] in [[San Diego]], [[California]]\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''Charlamagne & Friends''\n| Himself\n| 2013\u2013Present\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Guy Court]]''\n| Himself\n|\n|-\n| 2013, 2015\n| ''[[Wild 'N Out]]''\n| Himself\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Ride Along (film)|Ride Along]]''\n| Cop\n| Cameo appearance\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Catfish: The TV Show]]''\n| Himself\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 2015\u2013present\n| ''[[Uncommon Sense with Charlamagne]]''\n| Himself \n| Host\n|-\n| 2015 \n| ''[[Empire (2015 TV series)|Empire]]''\n| Himself \n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Grow House (film)|Grow House]]''\n| Black Jesus\n| Acting debut\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Bodied]]''\n|Hunnid Gramz\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Twitter|cthagod}}\n\n{{Gullah topics|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Charlamagne tha God}}\n[[Category:Radio personalities from New York City]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:African-American male comedians]]\n[[Category:American male comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:African-American comedians]]\n[[Category:African-American radio personalities]]\n[[Category:People from Moncks Corner, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Gullah]]\n[[Category:Catfish the TV Show hosts]]\n", "name_user": "74.141.134.180", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charlamagne_tha_God"}
{"title_page": "Spencer Dinwiddie", "text_new": "{{short description|American basketball player}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Spencer Dinwiddie\n| image = Spencer Dinwiddie (39916296274) (cropped).jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Dinwiddie with Brooklyn in 2018\n| number = 26\n| team = Brooklyn Nets\n| position = [[Point guard]]\n| league = [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1993|04|06}}\n| birth_place = [[Los Angeles, California]]\n| nationality = American\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 5\n| weight_lb = 215\n| high_school = [[William Howard Taft Charter High School (Los Angeles)|William Howard Taft]]<br>([[Woodland Hills, California]])\n| college = [[Colorado Buffaloes men's basketball|Colorado]] (2011\u20132014)\n| draft_year = 2014\n| draft_round = 2\n| draft_pick = 38\n| draft_team = [[Detroit Pistons]]\n| career_start = 2014\n| years1 = {{nbay|2014|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2015|end}}\n| team1 = [[Detroit Pistons]]\n| years2 = 2014\u20132016\n| team2 = \u2192[[Grand Rapids Drive]]\n| years3 = 2016\n| team3 = [[Windy City Bulls]]\n| years4 = {{nbay|2016|start}}\u2013present\n| team4 = [[Brooklyn Nets]]\n| highlights = \n* First-team [[List of All-Pac-12 Conference men's basketball teams|All-Pac-12]] ([[2012\u201313 Pac-12 Conference men's basketball season|2013]])\n| profile = spencer_dinwiddie\n| bbr = dinwisp01\n}}\n'''Spencer Gray Dinwiddie''' (born April 6, 1993) is an American professional [[basketball]] player for the [[Brooklyn Nets]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). He played [[college basketball]] for the [[Colorado Buffaloes men's basketball|Colorado Buffaloes]] and earned first-team [[List of All-Pac-12 Conference men's basketball teams|all-conference]] honors in the [[Pac-12 Conference men's basketball|Pac-12]] as a sophomore in 2013. He missed most of his junior year after injuring his [[anterior cruciate ligament]] (ACL). Dinwiddie recovered and was selected by the [[Detroit Pistons]] in the second round of the [[2014 NBA draft]]. After two seasons with the Pistons, he joined the Nets in December 2016. In December 2018 he signed a three-year contract extension with the Nets.\n\n==High school career==\nAt [[William Howard Taft High School (Los Angeles)|William Howard Taft High School]], Dinwiddie was recognized as one of the greatest standout athletes since [[Jordan Farmar]]. He averaged 5.9 points and 4.1 assists as the starting [[point guard]] alongside a fellow [[2014 NBA draft|2014 draftee]] in [[DeAndre Daniels]] at the conclusion of his junior season. Dinwiddie maximized his game as he began his final year representing the school, averaging 11.2 points and 7.7 assists. He was one of the most skilled passers in school history, and became the John R. Wooden California High School Player of the Year in 2011. However, [[Long Beach Polytechnic High School|Long Beach Poly]]'s Ryan Anderson was named [[California Mr. Basketball]]. Dinwiddie became just one of seven players that won the prestigious award as a senior. The powerful duo of Daniels and Dinwiddie won the city championship this season as well. This final season at Taft helped Dinwiddie gain the attention of colleges around the country. He chose to attend [[Colorado Buffaloes men's basketball|Colorado]] rather than [[Harvard Crimson men's basketball|Harvard]], [[Oregon Ducks men's basketball|Oregon]], [[Santa Clara Broncos men's basketball|Santa Clara]], or [[UNLV Runnin' Rebels basketball|UNLV]].\n\nConsidered a three-star recruit by [[Rivals.com]], Dinwiddie was listed as the No. 25 point guard and the No. 146 player in the nation in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Spencer Dinwiddie Recruiting Profile|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/footballrecruiting/basketball/recruiting/player-Spencer-Dinwiddie-113200|work=Rivals.com|accessdate=June 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\n\n===Freshman===\nIn the first regular season game for [[Colorado Buffaloes men's basketball|Colorado]], Dinwiddie made his collegiate debut in a 32-point victory over [[Fort Lewis Skyhawks|Fort Lewis]] with seven points and seven rebounds. He shot just 2-for-9 from the [[Field goal (basketball)|field]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Colorado 85, Fort Lewis 57|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=313150038|website=ESPN.com|date=November 11, 2011|access-date=June 30, 2014}}</ref> Dinwiddie reached double figures in his sixth appearance, which was against [[Georgia Bulldogs men's basketball|Georgia]]. This was the first time he had shot over .500 on field goals up till then. The [[California]] native led the team to this win and made three key free throws in the final seconds.<ref>{{cite web|title=Colorado 70, Georgia 68|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=313320038|website=ESPN.com|date=November 28, 2011|access-date=June 30, 2014}}</ref> Dinwiddie teamed with fellow freshman [[Askia Booker]], forming another duo on his new team. They combined for 677 points, making school history by scoring over 250 points each. At the conclusion of the season, they were the only Buffaloes to do so. Dinwiddie became a member of the Pac-12 Conference Tournament Championship Team. He led Colorado in free throw percentage and ranked third among freshmen in that category.<ref>{{cite web|title=Colorado Buffaloes 2011-12 Statistics|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/team/stats/_/id/38/year/2012/colorado-buffaloes|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=June 27, 2014}}</ref> By the end of the regular season, Dinwiddie had helped the team earn its first [[2012 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|NCAA Men's Basketball Tournament]] berth since the 2002\u201303 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=2002-03 Colorado Buffaloes Roster|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/schools/colorado/2003.html|website=Sports-reference.com|access-date=June 30, 2014}}</ref> Shooting [[Three-point field goal|three-pointers]] at .438 clip, Dinwiddie was named to the [[Pac-12 Conference|Pac-12]] All-Freshman Team with [[Tony Wroten]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Topham|first1=David|title=Detroit Pistons: Analyzing the Spencer Dinwiddie pick|url=http://isportsweb.com/2014/06/29/detroit-pistons-analyzing-spencer-dinwiddie-pick/|website=isportsweb.com|date=June 29, 2014|accessdate=June 30, 2014}}</ref> He was the only Pac-12 freshman to have a field-goal percentage of over .400 total.\n\n===Sophomore===\nThe departures of [[Carlon Brown]] and Nate Tomlinson were instrumental in Dinwiddie's breakout sophomore season. Leading the team in assists, they reached the [[2013 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|NCAA Men's Basketball Tournament]] for the second consecutive season, in which they reached the second round. It was the first time the team had reached back-to-back tournaments since the 1963 season. The Buffaloes won the 2012 [[Charleston Classic]], in which Dinwiddie took the role as starting [[small forward]] in the final three rounds. He was just one of two players \u2013 the other being Askia Booker \u2013 to start all 33 games. By the end of the season, Booker and Dinwiddie became the highest sophomore scoring tandem in school history. Dinwiddie led the team in assists 20 times and was the top scorer on 15 different occasions. He recorded 29 points in a home win over [[Colorado State Rams men's basketball|Colorado State]], which marked his own career-high scoring record. On February 10, 2012, Dinwiddie recorded a perfect game against [[Oregon State Beavers men's basketball|Oregon State]]. He shot 6-for-6 from the field, 4-for-4 from beyond the arc, and 8-for-8 on free throws. This set the school record for most points scored without missing a single shot.<ref>{{cite web|title=Spencer Dinwiddie Player Profile|url=http://basketball.realgm.com/player/Spencer-Dinwiddie/GameLogs/30385/NCAA/2013/All|website=RealGM.com|accessdate=June 30, 2014}}</ref> He made the remark, \"I see over people and I shoot over people... for the smaller point guards, they don't really get to contest me.\" The [[William Howard Taft Charter High School (Los Angeles)|Taft]] graduate stood {{height|ft=6|in=6}} by the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Thorburn|first1=Ryan|title=Men's basketball: CU Buffs will rely on Askia Booker and Spencer Dinwiddie|url=http://www.dailycamera.com/ci_21804927/mens-basketball-cu-buffs-will-rely-askia-booker|website=Buffzone.com|publisher=Daily Camera|date=October 18, 2012|accessdate=June 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Junior===\nDinwiddie continued to act as the leader of the [[Colorado Buffaloes men's basketball]] team through the beginning of his junior year. He helped the team win 14 of their first 16 regular season games, which made them one of the most successful underdogs in the country, most notably toppling the [[Kansas Jayhawks men's basketball|Kansas Jayhawks]] due to a game-winner from [[Askia Booker]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Dauster|first=Rob|title=Colorado needs game-winner to serve as a catalyst for Askia Booker (Video)|url=http://collegebasketballtalk.nbcsports.com/2013/12/07/askia-booker-beats-kansas-at-the-buzzer-video/|website=NBCSports.com|date=December 7, 2013|accessdate=June 27, 2014}}</ref> Dinwiddie was considered the catalyst for the unanticipated run from his team, however. On November 21, 2012, he shot a career-best 14-for-15 from the [[Free throw|free throw line]] against [[UC Santa Barbara Gauchos men's basketball|Santa Barbara]]. Colorado won each game in which their top scorer scored 20 or more points total.\n\nOn January 12, 2014, Dinwiddie suffered a career-threatening [[Anterior cruciate ligament|ACL]] injury against [[Washington Huskies men's basketball|Washington]], forcing him to sit out for the remainder of the season. As his junior season was cut short, the team finished the year just 23\u201312; their record was 14\u20132 while Dinwiddie was healthy. Dinwiddie reportedly made contact with Russ Paine, who helped [[Adrian Peterson]] recover from his ACL injury and become the 2012 [[National Football League Most Valuable Player Award|NFL MVP]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Goodman|first1=Jeff|title=Spencer Dinwiddie has torn ACL|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/10288706/colorado-buffaloes-star-spencer-dinwiddie-season|website=ESPN.com|date=January 15, 2014|accessdate=June 27, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Savage|first1=Brendan|title=Get to know, Spencer Dinwiddie: Detroit Pistons draft pick rehabbed with NFL star's therapist|url=http://www.mlive.com/pistons/index.ssf/2014/06/get_to_know_spencer_dinwiddie.html|website=MLive|date=June 27, 2014|accessdate=June 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn April 24, 2014, Dinwiddie declared for the NBA draft, foregoing his final year of college eligibility.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kensler|first1=Tom|title=CU Buffs point guard Spencer Dinwiddie declares for the 2014 NBA draft|url=http://www.denverpost.com/colleges/ci_25630281/cus-spencer-dinwiddie-will-forego-senior-year-declares|work=DenverPost.com|date=April 24, 2014|accessdate=April 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Detroit Pistons (2014\u20132016)===\n[[File:Spencer Dinwiddie, Ramon Sessions (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|left|Dinwiddie with the Pistons in February 2015]]\nDinwiddie was selected with the 38th overall pick by the [[Detroit Pistons]] in the [[2014 NBA draft]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Valdez|first1=Alexandria|title=Spencer Dinwiddie drafted by Pistons in second round at No. 38|url=http://www.denverpost.com/nuggets/ci_26043122/spencer-dinwiddie-drafted-by-pistons-second-round-at|work=DenverPost.com|date=June 26, 2014|accessdate=June 27, 2014}}</ref> He appeared in 34 games for the Pistons as a rookie, making one start<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/d/dinwisp01/gamelog/2015/|title=Spencer Dinwiddie 2014-15 Game Log|work=Basketball-Reference.com|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref> and receiving two assignments to the [[Grand Rapids Drive]], the Pistons' [[NBA Development League|D-League]] affiliate.<ref name=assignments>{{cite web|url=https://gleague.nba.com/all-time-nba-assignments/|title=All-Time NBA Assignments|work=NBA.com|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref> His lone start came on February 20, 2015, after a pair of trades left the Pistons short-handed. He had career highs of 12 points and nine assists in a 100\u201391 win over the [[Chicago Bulls]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20150220/CHIDET/gameinfo.html|title=Drummond, Dinwiddie lead thin Pistons past Bulls 100-91|work=NBA.com|date=February 20, 2015|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref> Eight days later, he scored a season-best 20 points to go with eight assists in 25 minutes off the bench in a 99\u201395 loss to the [[Washington Wizards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20150228/DETWAS/gameinfo.html|title=Wizards end losing streak with 99-95 win over Pistons|work=NBA.com|date=February 28, 2015|accessdate=February 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe 2015\u201316 season saw Dinwiddie appear in just 12 regular-season games for the Pistons, after spending the majority of the season in the D-League with the Grand Rapids Drive.<ref name=\"assignments\" /> After back-up [[Steve Blake]] opened the season in a miserable shooting slump,<ref name=review1516>{{cite web|last=Hinson|first=Steve|url=https://www.detroitbadboys.com/2016/5/10/11605952/2015-16-pistons-review-spencer-dinwiddie-running-out-of-chances|title=2015-16 Pistons Review: Spencer Dinwiddie running out of chances|work=detroitbadboys.com|date=May 10, 2016|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref> Dinwiddie received his first opportunity of the season in the tenth game, scoring 17 points on November 15 in a 97\u201385 loss to the [[Los Angeles Lakers]].<ref name=\"review1516\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400828038|title=Kobe Bryant, Jordan Clarkson lead Lakers past Pistons|work=ESPN.com|date=November 15, 2015|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref> However, after struggling in the next four games, he fell out of the rotation, compounded by Blake's form improvement and [[Brandon Jennings]] returning from injury.<ref name=\"review1516\" /> Dinwiddie played a season-high 29 minutes in the Pistons' regular-season finale on April 13, scoring 12 points in a 112\u2013110 overtime win over the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]].<ref name=br1516>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/d/dinwisp01/gamelog/2016/|title=Spencer Dinwiddie 2015-16 Game Log|work=Basketball-Reference.com|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/boxscore?gameId=400829107|title=Pistons vs. Cavaliers \u2013 Box Score|work=ESPN.com|date=April 13, 2016|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref> He then appeared in game two of the Pistons' 4\u20130 first-round playoff series loss to the Cavaliers.<ref name=\"br1516\" />\n\n===Chicago and Windy City Bulls (2016)===\nOn June 17, 2016, Dinwiddie was traded to the Chicago Bulls in exchange for [[Cameron Bairstow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/bulls/news/release/bulls-acquire-spencer-dinwiddie-cameron-bairstow|title=Bulls Acquire Spencer Dinwiddie For Cameron Bairstow|work=NBA.com|date=June 17, 2016|accessdate=June 17, 2016}}</ref> He was waived by the Bulls on July 7,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csnchicago.com/chicago-bulls/report-bulls-waive-point-guard-spencer-dinwiddie|title=Report: Bulls Waive Point Guard Spencer Dinwiddie|work=csnchicago.com|date=July 7, 2016|accessdate=July 28, 2016}}</ref> re-signed on July 28,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/bulls/news/bulls-sign-spencer-dinwiddie-728|title=Bulls Sign Spencer Dinwiddie|work=NBA.com|date=July 28, 2016|accessdate=July 28, 2016}}</ref> and waived again on October 21 after appearing in five preseason games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/bulls/news/release/bulls-waive-spencer-dinwiddie|title=Bulls Waive Spencer Dinwiddie|work=NBA.com|date=October 21, 2016|accessdate=October 21, 2016}}</ref> He then spent the start of the 2016\u201317 season with Chicago's D-League affiliate team, the [[Windy City Bulls]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://windycity.dleague.nba.com/news/windy-city-bulls-select-four-players-2016-d-league-draft-complete-training-camp-roster/|title=Windy City Bulls Select Four Players in 2016 D-League Draft to Complete Training Camp Roster|work=NBA.com|date=October 30, 2016|accessdate=December 5, 2016}}</ref> averaging 19.4 points, 8.1 assists and 3.7 rebounds over 37.4 minutes in nine games.<ref name=\"Brooklyn\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/nets/news/2016/12/08/brooklyn-nets-spencer-dinwiddie|title=Brooklyn Nets Sign Spencer Dinwiddie|work=NBA.com|date=December 8, 2016|accessdate=December 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Brooklyn Nets (2016\u2013present)===\nOn December 8, 2016, Dinwiddie signed with the [[Brooklyn Nets]].<ref name=\"Brooklyn\" /> On February 15, 2017, he scored 15 of his season-high 19 points in the fourth quarter of the Nets' 129\u2013125 loss to the [[Milwaukee Bucks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400900244|title=Antetokounmpo scores 33, Bucks hold off Nets 129-125|work=ESPN.com|date=February 15, 2017|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref> On April 8, 2017, in a 107\u2013106 win over the [[Chicago Bulls]], Dinwiddie made four free throws in the final 13.6 seconds and finished with 19 points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400900566|title=Wade returns but Nets hand Bulls potentially costly loss|work=ESPN.com|date=April 8, 2017|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn October 25, 2017, Dinwiddie scored a career-high 22 points and hit the go-ahead 3-pointer with 43 seconds left to lift the Nets to a 112\u2013107 win over the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400974809|title=Nets overcome James' triple-double, beat Cavs 112-107|work=ESPN.com|date=October 25, 2017|accessdate=October 25, 2017}}</ref> On October 29, he tied his career high with 22 points in a 124\u2013111 loss to the [[Denver Nuggets]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400974838|title=Murray, Jokic lead Nuggets to 124-111 win over Nets|work=ESPN.com|date=October 29, 2017|accessdate=October 29, 2017}}</ref> On November 17, he set a new career high with 25 points in a 118\u2013107 win over the [[Utah Jazz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400974970|title=Dinwiddie scores 25, leads Nets over Jazz, 118-107|work=ESPN.com|date=November 17, 2017|accessdate=November 17, 2017}}</ref> On December 14, he had 26 points in a 111\u2013104 loss to the [[New York Knicks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400975165|title=Knicks hold on to beat Nets after Porzingis leaves|work=ESPN.com|date=December 14, 2017|accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref> On December 23, he tied his career high with 26 points in a 123\u2013119 overtime loss to the [[Indiana Pacers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400975233|title=Oladipo scores 38, Pacers rally to beat Nets 123-119 in OT|work=ESPN.com|date=December 23, 2017|accessdate=December 23, 2017}}</ref> On January 3, 2018, he made the go-ahead jumper with 10.1 seconds left and tied his career high with 26 points, leading Brooklyn to a 98\u201397 victory over the [[Minnesota Timberwolves]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400975303|title=Nets cool off Timberwolves 98-97 on Dinwiddie's jumper|work=ESPN.com|date=January 3, 2018|accessdate=January 3, 2018}}</ref> On January 8, he set a new career high with 31 points in a 114\u2013113 overtime loss to the [[Toronto Raptors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400975338|title=DeRozan helps Raptors beat Nets in OT after Lowry hurt|work=ESPN.com|date=January 8, 2018|accessdate=January 8, 2018}}</ref> On January 12, he recorded a near triple-double with 20 points, 10 assists and nine rebounds in a 110\u2013105 win over the [[Atlanta Hawks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400975367|title=Dinwiddie takes charge in closing seconds, Nets beat Hawks|work=ESPN.com|date=January 12, 2018|accessdate=January 12, 2018}}</ref> On January 17, he had a career-high 13 assists in a 100\u201395 loss to the [[San Antonio Spurs]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Lewis|first=Brian|url=https://nypost.com/2018/01/18/spencer-dinwiddie-apologizes-to-the-nets-after-struggling-again/|title=Spencer Dinwiddie apologizes to the Nets after struggling again|work=nypost.com|date=January 17, 2018|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref> On February 17, Dinwiddie won the [[NBA All-Star Weekend Skills Challenge|Skills Challenge]] at [[2018 NBA All-Star Game|All-Star Weekend]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Labidou|first=Alex|url=http://www.nba.com/nets/news/2018/02/17/spencer-dinwiddie-thrilled-with-skills-challenge-win|title=Brooklyn Nets\u2019 Spencer Dinwiddie On Skills Challenge Win: It\u2019s Full Circle|work=NBA.com|date=February 17, 2018|accessdate=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn November 25, 2018, Dinwiddie scored 31 points in a 127\u2013125 loss to the [[Philadelphia 76ers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401070970|title=Butler's 3-pointer caps 76ers' rally to beat Nets|work=ESPN.com|date=November 25, 2018|accessdate=November 26, 2018}}</ref> On December 12, he scored a career-high 39 points in a 127\u2013124 win over the 76ers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071089|title=Dinwiddie scores career-best 39, Nets top 76ers 127-124|work=ESPN.com|date=December 12, 2018|accessdate=December 12, 2018}}</ref> The following day, he signed a reported three-year, $34 million contract extension with the Nets.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dowd|first=Tom|url=https://www.nba.com/nets/news/breaking/2018/12/13/brooklyn-nets-spencer-dinwiddie-gets-his-deal|title=Brooklyn Nets' Spencer Dinwiddie Gets His Deal|work=NBA.com|date=December 13, 2018|accessdate=December 14, 2018}}</ref> On December 26, he had 37 points and 11 assists off the bench in a 134\u2013132 double-overtime win over the [[Charlotte Hornets]]. It was his third 30-point game off the bench, matching the franchise record set by [[Cliff Robinson (basketball, born 1960)|Clifford T. Robinson]] in 1980\u201381.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071181|title=Nets beat Hornets 134-132 in 2OTs on Harris' late layup|work=ESPN.com|date=December 26, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018}}</ref> On January 16, 2019, he scored 25 of his 33 points in the fourth quarter and overtime of the Nets' 145\u2013142 win over the [[Houston Rockets]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071335|title=James Harden continues tear with 58, but Rockets fall in overtime to Nets|work=ESPN.com|date=January 16, 2019|accessdate=January 17, 2019}}</ref> On January 23, he scored a game-high 29 points in a 114\u2013110 win over the [[Orlando Magic]], thus scoring at least 25 points off the bench in 10 games, matching a franchise single-season record\u2014[[Robert Hawkins (basketball)|Bubbles Hawkins]] set the mark during the Nets' inaugural NBA season in 1976\u201377.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071381|title=Russell's double-double helps Nets edge Magic 114-110|work=ESPN.com|date=January 23, 2019|accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref> Two days later, it was revealed that a right thumb injury that he had originally hurt roughly two months earlier and had gotten progressively worse would require surgery, having suffered torn ligaments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nba/2019/01/25/dinwiddie-will-need-thumb-surgery-but-nets-unsure-how-soon/38956829/|title=Dinwiddie will need thumb surgery, but Nets unsure how soon|work=usatoday.com|date=January 25, 2019|accessdate=January 25, 2019|quote=Atkinson says the guard was originally hurt about two months ago and the injury has gotten progressively worse.}}</ref> He underwent surgery on January 28.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nba.com/nets/news/2019/01/28/spencer-dinwiddie-medical-update|title=Spencer Dinwiddie Medical Update|work=NBA.com|date=January 28, 2019|accessdate=January 28, 2019}}</ref> He returned to action on March 1 after missing 14 games, scoring 15 points off the bench in a 123\u2013112 loss to the Hornets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071602|title=Hornets end skid at 3, roll to 123-112 victory over Nets|work=ESPN.com|date=March 1, 2019|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref> With 28 points against the Cavaliers on March 6, Dinwiddie had his 14th 20-point game off the bench to set a Nets single-season record\u2014[[Darryl Dawkins]], [[Purvis Short]] and [[Orlando Woolridge]] all had 13.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071642|title=Dinwiddie leads Nets in 4th as they beat Cavs 113-107|work=ESPN.com|date=March 6, 2019|accessdate=March 7, 2019}}</ref> With 23 points against the Hawks on March 9, Dinwiddie surpassed [[Armen Gilliam]] in 1993\u201394 with the most single-season points in a reserve role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071660|title=Nets hold off Hawks 114-112 for 3rd straight win|work=ESPN.com|date=March 9, 2019|accessdate=March 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 28, 2020, Dinwiddie switched his jersey number from 8 to 26 after the approval of the NBA, in honor of the late [[Kobe Bryant]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Spencer Dinwiddie, Terrence Ross change jersey numbers after Kobe Bryant's passing |url=https://www.nba.com/article/2020/01/28/spencer-dinwiddie-terrence-ross-jersey-number-change |website=NBA.com |accessdate=January 28, 2020 |date=January 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==National team career==\nIn 2013, Dinwiddie was named to the USA Basketball Men's World University Games Team for the [[2013 Summer Universiade]] in [[Kazan, Russia]]. He was one of three players on Team USA to start all eight games. He averaged 7.9 points and 2.6 rebounds per game and led Team USA with 44 assists (5.5 apg) and with 12 steals (1.5 spg).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cubuffs.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=4162|title=Spencer Dinwiddie \u2013 2013-14 Men's Basketball Roster|work=cubuffs.com|accessdate=September 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDinwiddie is the son of Malcolm and Stephanie Dinwiddie, and he has a younger brother, Taylor.<ref name=\"coloradoprofile\">{{cite web|url=https://cubuffs.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=4162|title=Spencer Dinwiddie|work=cubuffs.com|accessdate=January 17, 2019}}</ref> Dinwiddie has a son with girlfriend Arielle Roberson, the sister of fellow NBA player [[Andr\u00e9 Roberson]].{{cn|date=November 2019}}\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===NBA===\n\n====Regular season====\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2014}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2014\u201315 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit]]\n| 34 || 1 || 13.4 || .302 || .185 || '''.912''' || 1.4 || 3.1 || .6 || .2 || 4.3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2015}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2015\u201316 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit]]\n| 12 || 0 || 13.3 || .352 || .100 || .576 || 1.4 || 1.8 || .3 || .0 || 4.8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2016}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2016\u201317 Brooklyn Nets season|Brooklyn]]\n| 59 || 18 || 22.6 || '''.444''' || '''.376''' || .792 || 2.8 || 3.1 || .7 || '''.4''' || 7.3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2017}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2017\u201318 Brooklyn Nets season|Brooklyn]]\n| '''80''' || '''58''' || '''28.8''' || .387 || .326 || .813 || '''3.2''' || '''6.6''' || '''.9''' || .3 || 12.6\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2018}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2018\u201319 Brooklyn Nets season|Brooklyn]]\n| 68 || 4 || 28.1 || .442 || .335 || .806 || 2.4 || 4.6 || .6 || .3 || '''16.8'''\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|Career\n| 253 || 81 || 24.4 || .408 || .323 || .801 || 2.6 || 4.5 || .7 || .3 || 11.0\n{{s-end}}\n\n====Playoffs====\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2016 NBA Playoffs|2016]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2015\u201316 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit]]\n| 1 || 0 || 2.0 || 1.000 || .000 || .000 || .0 || 1.0 || .0 || .0 || 2.0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2019 NBA Playoffs|2019]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2018\u201319 Brooklyn Nets season|Brooklyn]]\n| 5 || 0 || 26.2 || .435 || .375 || .714 || 2.6 || 1.6 || .4 || .0 || 14.6\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|Career\n| 6 || 0 || 22.2 || .444 || .375 || .714 || 2.2 || 1.5 || .3 || .0 || 12.5\n{{s-end}}\n\n===College===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2011\u201312 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2011\u201312]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2011\u201312 Colorado Buffaloes men's basketball team|Colorado]]\n| '''36''' || '''36''' || 27.4 || .402 || '''.438''' || .816 || '''3.6''' || 1.8 || .8 || .3 || 10.0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2012\u201313 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2012\u201313]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2012\u201313 Colorado Buffaloes men's basketball team|Colorado]]\n| 33 || 33 || '''32.5''' || .415 || .338 || .825 || 3.2 || 3.0 || 1.3 || '''.5''' || '''15.3'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2013\u201314 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2013\u201314]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2013\u201314 Colorado Buffaloes men's basketball team|Colorado]]\n| 17 || 17 || 31.1 || '''.466''' || .413 || '''.857''' || 3.1 || '''3.8''' || '''1.5''' || .2 || 14.7\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|Career\n| 86 || 86 || 30.1 || .420 || .386 || .830 || 3.3 || 2.6 || 1.1 || .3 || 13.0\n{{s-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal bar|Sports}}\n{{commons category}}\n{{basketballstats|nba=spencer_dinwiddie|bbr=d/dinwisp01}}\n* [https://cubuffs.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=4162 Colorado Buffaloes bio]\n\n{{Brooklyn Nets current roster}}\n{{2014 NBA Draft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dinwiddie, Spencer}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American basketball players]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from California]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn Nets players]]\n[[Category:Colorado Buffaloes men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Detroit Pistons draft picks]]\n[[Category:Detroit Pistons players]]\n[[Category:Grand Rapids Drive players]]\n[[Category:People from Woodland Hills, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Point guards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:William Howard Taft Charter High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Windy City Bulls players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American basketball player}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Spencer Dinwiddie\n| image = Spencer Dinwiddie (39916296274) (cropped).jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Dinwiddie with Brooklyn in 2018\n| number = 26\n| team = Brooklyn Nets\n| position = [[Point guard]]\n| league = [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1993|04|06}}\n| birth_place = [[Los Angeles, California]]\n| nationality = American\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 6\n| weight_lb = 215\n| high_school = [[William Howard Taft Charter High School (Los Angeles)|William Howard Taft]]<br>([[Woodland Hills, California]])\n| college = [[Colorado Buffaloes men's basketball|Colorado]] (2011\u20132014)\n| draft_year = 2014\n| draft_round = 2\n| draft_pick = 38\n| draft_team = [[Detroit Pistons]]\n| career_start = 2014\n| years1 = {{nbay|2014|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2015|end}}\n| team1 = [[Detroit Pistons]]\n| years2 = 2014\u20132016\n| team2 = \u2192[[Grand Rapids Drive]]\n| years3 = 2016\n| team3 = [[Windy City Bulls]]\n| years4 = {{nbay|2016|start}}\u2013present\n| team4 = [[Brooklyn Nets]]\n| highlights = \n* First-team [[List of All-Pac-12 Conference men's basketball teams|All-Pac-12]] ([[2012\u201313 Pac-12 Conference men's basketball season|2013]])\n| profile = spencer_dinwiddie\n| bbr = dinwisp01\n}}\n'''Spencer Gray Dinwiddie''' (born April 6, 1993) is an American professional [[basketball]] player for the [[Brooklyn Nets]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). He played [[college basketball]] for the [[Colorado Buffaloes men's basketball|Colorado Buffaloes]] and earned first-team [[List of All-Pac-12 Conference men's basketball teams|all-conference]] honors in the [[Pac-12 Conference men's basketball|Pac-12]] as a sophomore in 2013. He missed most of his junior year after injuring his [[anterior cruciate ligament]] (ACL). Dinwiddie recovered and was selected by the [[Detroit Pistons]] in the second round of the [[2014 NBA draft]]. After two seasons with the Pistons, he joined the Nets in December 2016. In December 2018 he signed a three-year contract extension with the Nets.\n\n==High school career==\nAt [[William Howard Taft High School (Los Angeles)|William Howard Taft High School]], Dinwiddie was recognized as one of the greatest standout athletes since [[Jordan Farmar]]. He averaged 5.9 points and 4.1 assists as the starting [[point guard]] alongside a fellow [[2014 NBA draft|2014 draftee]] in [[DeAndre Daniels]] at the conclusion of his junior season. Dinwiddie maximized his game as he began his final year representing the school, averaging 11.2 points and 7.7 assists. He was one of the most skilled passers in school history, and became the John R. Wooden California High School Player of the Year in 2011. However, [[Long Beach Polytechnic High School|Long Beach Poly]]'s Ryan Anderson was named [[California Mr. Basketball]]. Dinwiddie became just one of seven players that won the prestigious award as a senior. The powerful duo of Daniels and Dinwiddie won the city championship this season as well. This final season at Taft helped Dinwiddie gain the attention of colleges around the country. He chose to attend [[Colorado Buffaloes men's basketball|Colorado]] rather than [[Harvard Crimson men's basketball|Harvard]], [[Oregon Ducks men's basketball|Oregon]], [[Santa Clara Broncos men's basketball|Santa Clara]], or [[UNLV Runnin' Rebels basketball|UNLV]].\n\nConsidered a three-star recruit by [[Rivals.com]], Dinwiddie was listed as the No. 25 point guard and the No. 146 player in the nation in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Spencer Dinwiddie Recruiting Profile|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/footballrecruiting/basketball/recruiting/player-Spencer-Dinwiddie-113200|work=Rivals.com|accessdate=June 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\n\n===Freshman===\nIn the first regular season game for [[Colorado Buffaloes men's basketball|Colorado]], Dinwiddie made his collegiate debut in a 32-point victory over [[Fort Lewis Skyhawks|Fort Lewis]] with seven points and seven rebounds. He shot just 2-for-9 from the [[Field goal (basketball)|field]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Colorado 85, Fort Lewis 57|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=313150038|website=ESPN.com|date=November 11, 2011|access-date=June 30, 2014}}</ref> Dinwiddie reached double figures in his sixth appearance, which was against [[Georgia Bulldogs men's basketball|Georgia]]. This was the first time he had shot over .500 on field goals up till then. The [[California]] native led the team to this win and made three key free throws in the final seconds.<ref>{{cite web|title=Colorado 70, Georgia 68|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=313320038|website=ESPN.com|date=November 28, 2011|access-date=June 30, 2014}}</ref> Dinwiddie teamed with fellow freshman [[Askia Booker]], forming another duo on his new team. They combined for 677 points, making school history by scoring over 250 points each. At the conclusion of the season, they were the only Buffaloes to do so. Dinwiddie became a member of the Pac-12 Conference Tournament Championship Team. He led Colorado in free throw percentage and ranked third among freshmen in that category.<ref>{{cite web|title=Colorado Buffaloes 2011-12 Statistics|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/team/stats/_/id/38/year/2012/colorado-buffaloes|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=June 27, 2014}}</ref> By the end of the regular season, Dinwiddie had helped the team earn its first [[2012 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|NCAA Men's Basketball Tournament]] berth since the 2002\u201303 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=2002-03 Colorado Buffaloes Roster|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/schools/colorado/2003.html|website=Sports-reference.com|access-date=June 30, 2014}}</ref> Shooting [[Three-point field goal|three-pointers]] at .438 clip, Dinwiddie was named to the [[Pac-12 Conference|Pac-12]] All-Freshman Team with [[Tony Wroten]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Topham|first1=David|title=Detroit Pistons: Analyzing the Spencer Dinwiddie pick|url=http://isportsweb.com/2014/06/29/detroit-pistons-analyzing-spencer-dinwiddie-pick/|website=isportsweb.com|date=June 29, 2014|accessdate=June 30, 2014}}</ref> He was the only Pac-12 freshman to have a field-goal percentage of over .400 total.\n\n===Sophomore===\nThe departures of [[Carlon Brown]] and Nate Tomlinson were instrumental in Dinwiddie's breakout sophomore season. Leading the team in assists, they reached the [[2013 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|NCAA Men's Basketball Tournament]] for the second consecutive season, in which they reached the second round. It was the first time the team had reached back-to-back tournaments since the 1963 season. The Buffaloes won the 2012 [[Charleston Classic]], in which Dinwiddie took the role as starting [[small forward]] in the final three rounds. He was just one of two players \u2013 the other being Askia Booker \u2013 to start all 33 games. By the end of the season, Booker and Dinwiddie became the highest sophomore scoring tandem in school history. Dinwiddie led the team in assists 20 times and was the top scorer on 15 different occasions. He recorded 29 points in a home win over [[Colorado State Rams men's basketball|Colorado State]], which marked his own career-high scoring record. On February 10, 2012, Dinwiddie recorded a perfect game against [[Oregon State Beavers men's basketball|Oregon State]]. He shot 6-for-6 from the field, 4-for-4 from beyond the arc, and 8-for-8 on free throws. This set the school record for most points scored without missing a single shot.<ref>{{cite web|title=Spencer Dinwiddie Player Profile|url=http://basketball.realgm.com/player/Spencer-Dinwiddie/GameLogs/30385/NCAA/2013/All|website=RealGM.com|accessdate=June 30, 2014}}</ref> He made the remark, \"I see over people and I shoot over people... for the smaller point guards, they don't really get to contest me.\" The [[William Howard Taft Charter High School (Los Angeles)|Taft]] graduate stood {{height|ft=6|in=6}} by the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Thorburn|first1=Ryan|title=Men's basketball: CU Buffs will rely on Askia Booker and Spencer Dinwiddie|url=http://www.dailycamera.com/ci_21804927/mens-basketball-cu-buffs-will-rely-askia-booker|website=Buffzone.com|publisher=Daily Camera|date=October 18, 2012|accessdate=June 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Junior===\nDinwiddie continued to act as the leader of the [[Colorado Buffaloes men's basketball]] team through the beginning of his junior year. He helped the team win 14 of their first 16 regular season games, which made them one of the most successful underdogs in the country, most notably toppling the [[Kansas Jayhawks men's basketball|Kansas Jayhawks]] due to a game-winner from [[Askia Booker]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Dauster|first=Rob|title=Colorado needs game-winner to serve as a catalyst for Askia Booker (Video)|url=http://collegebasketballtalk.nbcsports.com/2013/12/07/askia-booker-beats-kansas-at-the-buzzer-video/|website=NBCSports.com|date=December 7, 2013|accessdate=June 27, 2014}}</ref> Dinwiddie was considered the catalyst for the unanticipated run from his team, however. On November 21, 2012, he shot a career-best 14-for-15 from the [[Free throw|free throw line]] against [[UC Santa Barbara Gauchos men's basketball|Santa Barbara]]. Colorado won each game in which their top scorer scored 20 or more points total.\n\nOn January 12, 2014, Dinwiddie suffered a career-threatening [[Anterior cruciate ligament|ACL]] injury against [[Washington Huskies men's basketball|Washington]], forcing him to sit out for the remainder of the season. As his junior season was cut short, the team finished the year just 23\u201312; their record was 14\u20132 while Dinwiddie was healthy. Dinwiddie reportedly made contact with Russ Paine, who helped [[Adrian Peterson]] recover from his ACL injury and become the 2012 [[National Football League Most Valuable Player Award|NFL MVP]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Goodman|first1=Jeff|title=Spencer Dinwiddie has torn ACL|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/10288706/colorado-buffaloes-star-spencer-dinwiddie-season|website=ESPN.com|date=January 15, 2014|accessdate=June 27, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Savage|first1=Brendan|title=Get to know, Spencer Dinwiddie: Detroit Pistons draft pick rehabbed with NFL star's therapist|url=http://www.mlive.com/pistons/index.ssf/2014/06/get_to_know_spencer_dinwiddie.html|website=MLive|date=June 27, 2014|accessdate=June 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn April 24, 2014, Dinwiddie declared for the NBA draft, foregoing his final year of college eligibility.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kensler|first1=Tom|title=CU Buffs point guard Spencer Dinwiddie declares for the 2014 NBA draft|url=http://www.denverpost.com/colleges/ci_25630281/cus-spencer-dinwiddie-will-forego-senior-year-declares|work=DenverPost.com|date=April 24, 2014|accessdate=April 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Detroit Pistons (2014\u20132016)===\n[[File:Spencer Dinwiddie, Ramon Sessions (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|left|Dinwiddie with the Pistons in February 2015]]\nDinwiddie was selected with the 38th overall pick by the [[Detroit Pistons]] in the [[2014 NBA draft]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Valdez|first1=Alexandria|title=Spencer Dinwiddie drafted by Pistons in second round at No. 38|url=http://www.denverpost.com/nuggets/ci_26043122/spencer-dinwiddie-drafted-by-pistons-second-round-at|work=DenverPost.com|date=June 26, 2014|accessdate=June 27, 2014}}</ref> He appeared in 34 games for the Pistons as a rookie, making one start<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/d/dinwisp01/gamelog/2015/|title=Spencer Dinwiddie 2014-15 Game Log|work=Basketball-Reference.com|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref> and receiving two assignments to the [[Grand Rapids Drive]], the Pistons' [[NBA Development League|D-League]] affiliate.<ref name=assignments>{{cite web|url=https://gleague.nba.com/all-time-nba-assignments/|title=All-Time NBA Assignments|work=NBA.com|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref> His lone start came on February 20, 2015, after a pair of trades left the Pistons short-handed. He had career highs of 12 points and nine assists in a 100\u201391 win over the [[Chicago Bulls]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20150220/CHIDET/gameinfo.html|title=Drummond, Dinwiddie lead thin Pistons past Bulls 100-91|work=NBA.com|date=February 20, 2015|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref> Eight days later, he scored a season-best 20 points to go with eight assists in 25 minutes off the bench in a 99\u201395 loss to the [[Washington Wizards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20150228/DETWAS/gameinfo.html|title=Wizards end losing streak with 99-95 win over Pistons|work=NBA.com|date=February 28, 2015|accessdate=February 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe 2015\u201316 season saw Dinwiddie appear in just 12 regular-season games for the Pistons, after spending the majority of the season in the D-League with the Grand Rapids Drive.<ref name=\"assignments\" /> After back-up [[Steve Blake]] opened the season in a miserable shooting slump,<ref name=review1516>{{cite web|last=Hinson|first=Steve|url=https://www.detroitbadboys.com/2016/5/10/11605952/2015-16-pistons-review-spencer-dinwiddie-running-out-of-chances|title=2015-16 Pistons Review: Spencer Dinwiddie running out of chances|work=detroitbadboys.com|date=May 10, 2016|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref> Dinwiddie received his first opportunity of the season in the tenth game, scoring 17 points on November 15 in a 97\u201385 loss to the [[Los Angeles Lakers]].<ref name=\"review1516\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400828038|title=Kobe Bryant, Jordan Clarkson lead Lakers past Pistons|work=ESPN.com|date=November 15, 2015|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref> However, after struggling in the next four games, he fell out of the rotation, compounded by Blake's form improvement and [[Brandon Jennings]] returning from injury.<ref name=\"review1516\" /> Dinwiddie played a season-high 29 minutes in the Pistons' regular-season finale on April 13, scoring 12 points in a 112\u2013110 overtime win over the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]].<ref name=br1516>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/d/dinwisp01/gamelog/2016/|title=Spencer Dinwiddie 2015-16 Game Log|work=Basketball-Reference.com|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/boxscore?gameId=400829107|title=Pistons vs. Cavaliers \u2013 Box Score|work=ESPN.com|date=April 13, 2016|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref> He then appeared in game two of the Pistons' 4\u20130 first-round playoff series loss to the Cavaliers.<ref name=\"br1516\" />\n\n===Chicago and Windy City Bulls (2016)===\nOn June 17, 2016, Dinwiddie was traded to the Chicago Bulls in exchange for [[Cameron Bairstow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/bulls/news/release/bulls-acquire-spencer-dinwiddie-cameron-bairstow|title=Bulls Acquire Spencer Dinwiddie For Cameron Bairstow|work=NBA.com|date=June 17, 2016|accessdate=June 17, 2016}}</ref> He was waived by the Bulls on July 7,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csnchicago.com/chicago-bulls/report-bulls-waive-point-guard-spencer-dinwiddie|title=Report: Bulls Waive Point Guard Spencer Dinwiddie|work=csnchicago.com|date=July 7, 2016|accessdate=July 28, 2016}}</ref> re-signed on July 28,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/bulls/news/bulls-sign-spencer-dinwiddie-728|title=Bulls Sign Spencer Dinwiddie|work=NBA.com|date=July 28, 2016|accessdate=July 28, 2016}}</ref> and waived again on October 21 after appearing in five preseason games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/bulls/news/release/bulls-waive-spencer-dinwiddie|title=Bulls Waive Spencer Dinwiddie|work=NBA.com|date=October 21, 2016|accessdate=October 21, 2016}}</ref> He then spent the start of the 2016\u201317 season with Chicago's D-League affiliate team, the [[Windy City Bulls]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://windycity.dleague.nba.com/news/windy-city-bulls-select-four-players-2016-d-league-draft-complete-training-camp-roster/|title=Windy City Bulls Select Four Players in 2016 D-League Draft to Complete Training Camp Roster|work=NBA.com|date=October 30, 2016|accessdate=December 5, 2016}}</ref> averaging 19.4 points, 8.1 assists and 3.7 rebounds over 37.4 minutes in nine games.<ref name=\"Brooklyn\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/nets/news/2016/12/08/brooklyn-nets-spencer-dinwiddie|title=Brooklyn Nets Sign Spencer Dinwiddie|work=NBA.com|date=December 8, 2016|accessdate=December 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Brooklyn Nets (2016\u2013present)===\nOn December 8, 2016, Dinwiddie signed with the [[Brooklyn Nets]].<ref name=\"Brooklyn\" /> On February 15, 2017, he scored 15 of his season-high 19 points in the fourth quarter of the Nets' 129\u2013125 loss to the [[Milwaukee Bucks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400900244|title=Antetokounmpo scores 33, Bucks hold off Nets 129-125|work=ESPN.com|date=February 15, 2017|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref> On April 8, 2017, in a 107\u2013106 win over the [[Chicago Bulls]], Dinwiddie made four free throws in the final 13.6 seconds and finished with 19 points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400900566|title=Wade returns but Nets hand Bulls potentially costly loss|work=ESPN.com|date=April 8, 2017|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn October 25, 2017, Dinwiddie scored a career-high 22 points and hit the go-ahead 3-pointer with 43 seconds left to lift the Nets to a 112\u2013107 win over the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400974809|title=Nets overcome James' triple-double, beat Cavs 112-107|work=ESPN.com|date=October 25, 2017|accessdate=October 25, 2017}}</ref> On October 29, he tied his career high with 22 points in a 124\u2013111 loss to the [[Denver Nuggets]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400974838|title=Murray, Jokic lead Nuggets to 124-111 win over Nets|work=ESPN.com|date=October 29, 2017|accessdate=October 29, 2017}}</ref> On November 17, he set a new career high with 25 points in a 118\u2013107 win over the [[Utah Jazz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400974970|title=Dinwiddie scores 25, leads Nets over Jazz, 118-107|work=ESPN.com|date=November 17, 2017|accessdate=November 17, 2017}}</ref> On December 14, he had 26 points in a 111\u2013104 loss to the [[New York Knicks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400975165|title=Knicks hold on to beat Nets after Porzingis leaves|work=ESPN.com|date=December 14, 2017|accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref> On December 23, he tied his career high with 26 points in a 123\u2013119 overtime loss to the [[Indiana Pacers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400975233|title=Oladipo scores 38, Pacers rally to beat Nets 123-119 in OT|work=ESPN.com|date=December 23, 2017|accessdate=December 23, 2017}}</ref> On January 3, 2018, he made the go-ahead jumper with 10.1 seconds left and tied his career high with 26 points, leading Brooklyn to a 98\u201397 victory over the [[Minnesota Timberwolves]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400975303|title=Nets cool off Timberwolves 98-97 on Dinwiddie's jumper|work=ESPN.com|date=January 3, 2018|accessdate=January 3, 2018}}</ref> On January 8, he set a new career high with 31 points in a 114\u2013113 overtime loss to the [[Toronto Raptors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400975338|title=DeRozan helps Raptors beat Nets in OT after Lowry hurt|work=ESPN.com|date=January 8, 2018|accessdate=January 8, 2018}}</ref> On January 12, he recorded a near triple-double with 20 points, 10 assists and nine rebounds in a 110\u2013105 win over the [[Atlanta Hawks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400975367|title=Dinwiddie takes charge in closing seconds, Nets beat Hawks|work=ESPN.com|date=January 12, 2018|accessdate=January 12, 2018}}</ref> On January 17, he had a career-high 13 assists in a 100\u201395 loss to the [[San Antonio Spurs]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Lewis|first=Brian|url=https://nypost.com/2018/01/18/spencer-dinwiddie-apologizes-to-the-nets-after-struggling-again/|title=Spencer Dinwiddie apologizes to the Nets after struggling again|work=nypost.com|date=January 17, 2018|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref> On February 17, Dinwiddie won the [[NBA All-Star Weekend Skills Challenge|Skills Challenge]] at [[2018 NBA All-Star Game|All-Star Weekend]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Labidou|first=Alex|url=http://www.nba.com/nets/news/2018/02/17/spencer-dinwiddie-thrilled-with-skills-challenge-win|title=Brooklyn Nets\u2019 Spencer Dinwiddie On Skills Challenge Win: It\u2019s Full Circle|work=NBA.com|date=February 17, 2018|accessdate=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn November 25, 2018, Dinwiddie scored 31 points in a 127\u2013125 loss to the [[Philadelphia 76ers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401070970|title=Butler's 3-pointer caps 76ers' rally to beat Nets|work=ESPN.com|date=November 25, 2018|accessdate=November 26, 2018}}</ref> On December 12, he scored a career-high 39 points in a 127\u2013124 win over the 76ers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071089|title=Dinwiddie scores career-best 39, Nets top 76ers 127-124|work=ESPN.com|date=December 12, 2018|accessdate=December 12, 2018}}</ref> The following day, he signed a reported three-year, $34 million contract extension with the Nets.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dowd|first=Tom|url=https://www.nba.com/nets/news/breaking/2018/12/13/brooklyn-nets-spencer-dinwiddie-gets-his-deal|title=Brooklyn Nets' Spencer Dinwiddie Gets His Deal|work=NBA.com|date=December 13, 2018|accessdate=December 14, 2018}}</ref> On December 26, he had 37 points and 11 assists off the bench in a 134\u2013132 double-overtime win over the [[Charlotte Hornets]]. It was his third 30-point game off the bench, matching the franchise record set by [[Cliff Robinson (basketball, born 1960)|Clifford T. Robinson]] in 1980\u201381.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071181|title=Nets beat Hornets 134-132 in 2OTs on Harris' late layup|work=ESPN.com|date=December 26, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018}}</ref> On January 16, 2019, he scored 25 of his 33 points in the fourth quarter and overtime of the Nets' 145\u2013142 win over the [[Houston Rockets]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071335|title=James Harden continues tear with 58, but Rockets fall in overtime to Nets|work=ESPN.com|date=January 16, 2019|accessdate=January 17, 2019}}</ref> On January 23, he scored a game-high 29 points in a 114\u2013110 win over the [[Orlando Magic]], thus scoring at least 25 points off the bench in 10 games, matching a franchise single-season record\u2014[[Robert Hawkins (basketball)|Bubbles Hawkins]] set the mark during the Nets' inaugural NBA season in 1976\u201377.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071381|title=Russell's double-double helps Nets edge Magic 114-110|work=ESPN.com|date=January 23, 2019|accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref> Two days later, it was revealed that a right thumb injury that he had originally hurt roughly two months earlier and had gotten progressively worse would require surgery, having suffered torn ligaments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nba/2019/01/25/dinwiddie-will-need-thumb-surgery-but-nets-unsure-how-soon/38956829/|title=Dinwiddie will need thumb surgery, but Nets unsure how soon|work=usatoday.com|date=January 25, 2019|accessdate=January 25, 2019|quote=Atkinson says the guard was originally hurt about two months ago and the injury has gotten progressively worse.}}</ref> He underwent surgery on January 28.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nba.com/nets/news/2019/01/28/spencer-dinwiddie-medical-update|title=Spencer Dinwiddie Medical Update|work=NBA.com|date=January 28, 2019|accessdate=January 28, 2019}}</ref> He returned to action on March 1 after missing 14 games, scoring 15 points off the bench in a 123\u2013112 loss to the Hornets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071602|title=Hornets end skid at 3, roll to 123-112 victory over Nets|work=ESPN.com|date=March 1, 2019|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref> With 28 points against the Cavaliers on March 6, Dinwiddie had his 14th 20-point game off the bench to set a Nets single-season record\u2014[[Darryl Dawkins]], [[Purvis Short]] and [[Orlando Woolridge]] all had 13.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071642|title=Dinwiddie leads Nets in 4th as they beat Cavs 113-107|work=ESPN.com|date=March 6, 2019|accessdate=March 7, 2019}}</ref> With 23 points against the Hawks on March 9, Dinwiddie surpassed [[Armen Gilliam]] in 1993\u201394 with the most single-season points in a reserve role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071660|title=Nets hold off Hawks 114-112 for 3rd straight win|work=ESPN.com|date=March 9, 2019|accessdate=March 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 28, 2020, Dinwiddie switched his jersey number from 8 to 26 after the approval of the NBA, in honor of the late [[Kobe Bryant]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Spencer Dinwiddie, Terrence Ross change jersey numbers after Kobe Bryant's passing |url=https://www.nba.com/article/2020/01/28/spencer-dinwiddie-terrence-ross-jersey-number-change |website=NBA.com |accessdate=January 28, 2020 |date=January 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==National team career==\nIn 2013, Dinwiddie was named to the USA Basketball Men's World University Games Team for the [[2013 Summer Universiade]] in [[Kazan, Russia]]. He was one of three players on Team USA to start all eight games. He averaged 7.9 points and 2.6 rebounds per game and led Team USA with 44 assists (5.5 apg) and with 12 steals (1.5 spg).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cubuffs.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=4162|title=Spencer Dinwiddie \u2013 2013-14 Men's Basketball Roster|work=cubuffs.com|accessdate=September 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDinwiddie is the son of Malcolm and Stephanie Dinwiddie, and he has a younger brother, Taylor.<ref name=\"coloradoprofile\">{{cite web|url=https://cubuffs.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=4162|title=Spencer Dinwiddie|work=cubuffs.com|accessdate=January 17, 2019}}</ref> Dinwiddie has a son with girlfriend Arielle Roberson, the sister of fellow NBA player [[Andr\u00e9 Roberson]].{{cn|date=November 2019}}\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===NBA===\n\n====Regular season====\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2014}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2014\u201315 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit]]\n| 34 || 1 || 13.4 || .302 || .185 || '''.912''' || 1.4 || 3.1 || .6 || .2 || 4.3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2015}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2015\u201316 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit]]\n| 12 || 0 || 13.3 || .352 || .100 || .576 || 1.4 || 1.8 || .3 || .0 || 4.8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2016}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2016\u201317 Brooklyn Nets season|Brooklyn]]\n| 59 || 18 || 22.6 || '''.444''' || '''.376''' || .792 || 2.8 || 3.1 || .7 || '''.4''' || 7.3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2017}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2017\u201318 Brooklyn Nets sea